	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ok, what the guy before me has said about not twisting chords...IMHO and MANY other bards will agree with me, you definitely should. As far as twisting Jig or Hymn, DON'T. Your hymn at 18 either heals 9 or 10 per tick, and at level 18 your group is going to be taking so much damage that during battle those hit points aren't going to mean much. I would suggest, twisting Denon's Discord, Chords, Bellow, Anthem (warsong if soloing, its haste is way better), and if you're fighting casters, Guardian Rhythms. You can cut out using bellow excessively, only enough to throw in an extra smidge of damage (although it adds up quickly), but keeping the entire party hasted with anthem and your DoTs (Chords and Denon's) is a larger priority. If you're good, you can keep the haste flowing, the DoTs hurting, and you can Bellow or add to resistances to kill the mobs faster or prevent nukes and other spells from affecting your party too much. At 20 you get the mana song which is GREAT during downtime, as well as Hymn. While it may be tiring, twist Hymn and the mana song together during downtime to keep the tanks healed, the casters full of mana, and just do what you feel is best in battle (the combo I mentioned earlier is great for almost all situations until you get snare at 20). Doing this, I've found that I can do good tank damage (Blackjack and Stormfeather Talons: 8/23 and 7/21, not that twinked at all), and keep the songs twisted to maximize effectiveness. In short, I would reccomend not twisting hymn anymore at your level during battles, only during downtime, where it makes a HUGE difference. <br><br>Fermata<br>Bard of the 34th Song<br>Brell Serilis<br>"I see dumb people. They're everywhere. They don't even know that they're dumb."<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
